{{more citations needed|date=April 2015}} {{Infobox person | name = Abraham-Leib Monsohn | image = Abraham-Leib_Monsohn_in_Ottoman_fez.png | image_size = 180px | caption = Abraham-Leib Monsohn in his [[fez]] as map-maker for the Ottomans in Jerusalem | birth_date = January 1871 | birth_place = Jerusalem, Eretz Israel | death_date = March 14, 1930 | death_place = Jerusalem, Eretz Israel | residence = Jerusalem, Eretz Israel | occupation = [[Lithographer]] | spouse = [[Rachel-Leah Miriam (Honig) Monsohn]] | parents = Yoel Yosef Shimon Monsohn, Gittel (Yofe) Monsohn | children = David, Menachem Mendel, Yosef, Moshe, Shimon, Raytse (Barmacz) }}
The '''A.L. Monsohn Lithographic Press''' (דפוס אבן א"ל מאנזאהן) was established in [[Jerusalem]] in 1892 by Abraham-Leib (or Avrom-Leyb) [[Monsohn Family of Jerusalem|Monsohn]] II (Jerusalem, c.1871-1930) and his brother Moshe-Mordechai (Meyshe-Mordkhe).<ref>{{cite book|last1= Grayevski |first1= Pinḥas |title= Osef temunot (albom) mi-yelide ha-aretz: rabbanim, ḥakhamim u-sofrim, ‘asqane ha-ṣibbur |date=1930|publisher= Yerushalayim : Pinḥas Grayevski |url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/osef-temunot-albom-mi-yelide-ha-arets-rabanim-hakhamim-u-sofrim-askane-ha-tsibur/oclc/53190977&referer=brief_results/}}</ref> Sponsored by members of the Hamburger family,<ref name="On the lithographic activities of Abraham-Leib and Moshe-Mordechai Monsohn in Jerusalem, in ''Ha-Melitz'' no. 203, 19 September 1897.">{{cite news|url= http://www.jpress.nli.org.il/Olive/APA/NLI_heb/?action=search&text=%D7%9C%D7%99%D7%91%20%D7%9E%D7%90%D7%A0%D7%96%D7%90%D7%94%D7%9F|title= "The Holy Land: Letters from Jerusalem," ''Ha-Melitz'', Jerusalem, 19 September 1897}}</ref> the brothers had been sent to [[Frankfurt]] in 1890 to study [[lithography]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Monzon|first1=Shimon|last2=Gavish|first2=Galia|last3=Appleton|first3=Judith|title= A. L. Monsohn Print, 1892-1992: Baramatz - From Lithography to Offset : [exhibition catalogue]|date=2009|publisher=Jerusalem : Isaac Kaplan Old Yishuv Court Museum|url= https://www.worldcat.org/title/defus-al-monzon-1892-1992-baramats-mi-litografyah-le-ofset/oclc/454287200&referer=brief_results/}}</ref> Upon returning to Jerusalem with a [[Printing press|hand press]], they established the A.L. Monsohn Lithographic Press in the [[Old City of Jerusalem]]. At first it was situated in [[Bab al-Huta]]; it was later moved to the courtyard opposite what is today the Old Yishuv Court Museum ([[Hebrew]]: [[:he:מוזיאון חצר היישוב הישן|מוזיאון חצר היישוב הישן]]) at 6 Or Ha-Hayim Street in the [[Jewish Quarter (Jerusalem)|Jewish Quarter]], where Abraham-Leib Monsohn lived with his family.<ref>{{cite book|last1= Grayevski |first1=Pinḥas |title=Mi-ginzei Yerushalayim,ḥoveret 6,pp. 29-30|date=1930|publisher=Yerushalayim :Tsiyon |url= https://www.worldcat.org/title/mi-ginze-yerushalayim-kolel-teudot-historiyot-le-toldot-ha-yishuv-ha-yehudi-be-erez-yisrael/oclc/13222572&referer=brief_results/}}</ref> Leaving the Old City, the press was relocated to the [[Mamilla]] section of Jerusalem, and later to Yosef Ziv Street in the [[Tel Arza]] neighborhood. The Monsohn Press produced about 300 color prints per day, the only color printing done at the time in Jerusalem. In 1894 they imported a new machine which could print 1,000 copies a day—a great advance in local printing. The founders of the Monsohn press produced Jewish-themed color [[postcards]], [[greeting cards]], [[Jewish National Fund]] stamps, and maps documenting the evolution of the Jewish settlement in [[Eretz Israel]] in the nineteenth-twentieth centuries; religious material such as decorative plaques for [[synagogues]],<ref>{{cite book|last1= Sarfati |first1= Rachel | title= Offerings from Jerusalem: Portrayals of Holy Places by Jewish Artists |date=2002|publisher= Yerushalayim : Muze’on Yisra’el |url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/offerings-from-jerusalem-portrayals-of-holy-places-by-jewish-artists/oclc/690023193&referer=brief_results/}}</ref> portraits of [[Old Yishuv]] rabbis such as [[Shmuel Salant]], [[Mizrah]] posters indicating the direction of prayer for synagogues, memorial posters, and posters for [[Sukkot]] booths;,<ref>{{cite book|last1= Fischer|first1= Yona |last2= Peled|first2= Haviva|title= Omanut ve-umanut be-Erez-Yisrael ba-meah ha-tesha-‘esreh|date=1979|publisher= Yerushalayim : Muze’on Yisra’el |url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/omanut-ve-umanut-be-erets-yisrael-ba-meah-ha-tesha-esreh/oclc/18244616&referer=brief_results/}}</ref> color frontispieces for books such as Pentateuch volumes and the early song collections of [[Abraham Zvi Idelsohn]] (e.g., ''Shire Zion'', Jerusalem 1908); artistic wedding invitations; and later, government posters;<ref name="Article on the Monsohn press posters.">{{cite news|url=http://www.naamat.org/images/stories/magazine/haganahposters.pdf |title=Molly Abramowitz, "The Mysterious Case of the Haganah Posters," Na’amat Women, Summer 2009, 12-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518101648/http://www.naamat.org/images/stories/magazine/haganahposters.pdf |archivedate=2015-05-18 }}</ref> and labels, packaging and advertisements for the pioneering entrepreneurs of Eretz Israel. Many of the postcards and [[map]]s can be seen online,<ref name="A Facebook page dedicated to Zvi Kadesh Monsohn edition postcards featuring Jerusalem sites.">{{cite news|url=https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.602146599892451.1073741832.601215186652259&type=1|title= Zvi Kadesh Monsohn Edition}}</ref><ref name="A Monsohn map in the Jewish National and University Library, Jerusalem.">{{cite news|url=http://jnul.huji.ac.il/dl/maps/pal/html/eng/pal002369246.htm |title=Map of Eretz Israel |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230846/http://jnul.huji.ac.il/dl/maps/pal/html/eng/pal002369246.htm |archivedate=2016-03-03 }}</ref> as can the artistic invitations to his children's weddings which Monsohn published in the Jerusalem Hebrew press (e.g., that for his son [[Menachem Mendel Monsohn]] and his wife Zipporah in the 24 June 1914 issue of ''Moria'').<ref name="Invitation to wedding of Menachem Mendel and Zipporah in Moria, 24 June 1914.">{{cite news|url= http://jpress.org.il/Olive/APA/NLI_heb/?action=tab&tab=browse&pub=MRH|title= "Invitation to wedding of Menachem Mendel Monsohn and Zipporah Yehudith Schwartz," ''Moria'', Jerusalem, June 24, 1914}}</ref> The Monsohn Press received special permission from the city's [[rabbis]] to print for [[Christians]] and [[Moslems]], so long as the material could not be used to [[Missionary|missionize]].<ref name="A news article on nineteenth-century Jewish printing in Jerusalem.">{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Magazine/Features/Making-an-imprint|title=Making an Imprint}}</ref> While Eretz Israel was under [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] control, Abraham-Leib Monsohn also printed the maps for the Ottoman military leader [[Djemal Pasha]], in his headquarters in [[Mount Scopus]].
For years, the Monsohn (later, Monson/Monzon) Press was considered the best and most innovative in the country—pioneering in such techniques as [[Hot stamping|gold-embossing]] and [[offset printing]], among others. Early items for tourists included collections of ''[[Flowers of the Holy Land]]'' (c. 1910-1918)—pressed local flowers accompanied by scenes from the Eretz Israel countryside and relevant verses from the Bible, edited by [[Jsac Chagise]] (or Itzhak Haggis), an immigrant from Vitebsk, and bound in carved olive wood boards.<ref name="Online exchanges about Flowers and Views of the Holy Lanod.">{{cite news|url= https://thebarrowboy.wordpress.com/2009/01/06/flowers-of-the-holy-land/|title=Flowers and Views of the Holy Land}}</ref> Shortly after World War I Monsohn (now spelled מונזון) used [[zincography]] to produce the prints included in the Hebrew ''[[Gannenu]]'' educational booklets for young children illustrated by [[Ze'ev Raban]] of the [[Bezalel Academy of Art and Design]] and printed in Jerusalem by [[Hayim Refael Hakohen]] (vol. 1, 1919; vols. 2-3, 1920).<ref>{{cite book|title= Bibliography of the Hebrew Book|url= http://aleph.nli.org.il:80/F/?func=direct&doc_number=000117639&local_base=MBI01}}</ref> In 1934 Monsohn moved into the new, western part of Jerusalem, in a shop with four presses and 30 workers, including Abraham-Leib's sons, David, Yosef, Moshe and Shimon, and his daughter Raytse's husband, Abraham Barmacz. The concern did business with all sectors of the city's population, including [[Arabs]], for whom they printed in [[Arabic]]. Among their clients were members of the [[Ginio]], [[Havilio]], and [[Strauss (company)|Elite]] families, and [[Shemen (manufacturer)|Shemen]], [[Dubek]], and other renowned national brands, manufacturing products such as [[wine]], [[candy|candies]], [[oil]], and [[cigarettes]].<ref>{{cite book|last1= Monzon|first1= Arye|title= The Monzon Family History in Jerusalem|date= 2007|publisher= Jerusalem : The author|url= http://www.bentisser.com/uploads/1/5/4/1/15410790/monzon_family_english.pdf/}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> They also printed [[Film poster|movie]] and [[Poster#Travel posters|travel posters]], and government posters, [[postcards]] and [[documents]], hotel luggage labels, receipts for [[Bikur Cholim Hospital]] and other local institutions, metal charity boxes, Melnik, Rosin & Co. (Jerusalem) embroidery designs (c.1900), and cloth covers for ''[[hallot]]''. During the [[Austerity in Israel|Tzena]] austerity period Monsohn was the exclusive printer of government [[coupon book]]lets.
Shimon Monson (or Monzon, b. 1907; son of Abraham-Leib II) and Shimon Barmacz (b. 1922; son of Raytsa Monsohn Barmacz [b. 1901]), recipient of the [[Yakir Yerushalayim]] award),<ref name="A news article announcing the death of Shimon Barmatz in 2009.">{{cite news|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/Flash.aspx/160054|title=Pre-State Fighter Shimon Barmatz Dead at 87}}</ref> were responsible for the press in its final stage, during which it also produced [[Jewish National Fund]] [[calendars]], color [[map]]s, illustrations of [[animals]] in the [[Bible]], [[tourist]] brochures, and printed [[books]], especially [[photo-offset]] editions of sacred works, of which they printed over 80 (e.g., ''Mishnah Berurah'', 6 vols., 1950;<ref>{{cite book|title= Bibliography of the Hebrew Book|url= http://aleph.nli.org.il/F/PILYY8PJ3H682A78GYM7PAH7BYS3SAJBTJQVNTAT4Q9FPYBY38-10276?func=full-set-set&set_number=008521&set_entry=000047&format=999}}</ref> ''Miqra'ot Gedolot'', 5 vols., 1955;<ref>{{cite book|title= Bibliography of the Hebrew Book|url= http://aleph.nli.org.il/F/PILYY8PJ3H682A78GYM7PAH7BYS3SAJBTJQVNTAT4Q9FPYBY38-04562?func=find-acc&acc_sequence=000090361}}</ref> ''Ḥoq Le-Yisrael'', 5 vols., 1956;<ref>{{cite book|title= Bibliography of the Hebrew Book|url= http://aleph.nli.org.il/F/PILYY8PJ3H682A78GYM7PAH7BYS3SAJBTJQVNTAT4Q9FPYBY38-20287?func=full-set-set&set_number=008521&set_entry=000039&format=999}}</ref> ''Shulhan Arukh'', 2 vols., 1956-1957;<ref>{{cite book|title= Bibliography of the Hebrew Book|url= http://aleph.nli.org.il/F/PILYY8PJ3H682A78GYM7PAH7BYS3SAJBTJQVNTAT4Q9FPYBY38-16400?func=full-set-set&set_number=008521&set_entry=000035&format=999}}</ref> ''Zohar'', 5 vols., 1958-1960;<ref>{{cite book|title= Bibliography of the Hebrew Book|url= http://aleph.nli.org.il/F/PILYY8PJ3H682A78GYM7PAH7BYS3SAJBTJQVNTAT4Q9FPYBY38-21372?func=full-set-set&set_number=008521&set_entry=000028&format=999}}</ref> ''Moreh Nevukhim'', 3 vols., 1960<ref>{{cite book|title= Bibliography of the Hebrew Book|url= http://aleph.nli.org.il/F/PILYY8PJ3H682A78GYM7PAH7BYS3SAJBTJQVNTAT4Q9FPYBY38-20168?func=full-set-set&set_number=008521&set_entry=000013&format=999}}</ref>). In 1955 Shimon Monson also printed the 1955 first Jerusalem edition of [[Vladimir Nabokov]]'s ''[[Lolita]]'' for the [[Olympia Press]] (2 vols.). The revolutionary [[Koren Publishers Jerusalem]] Bible was printed at the press of Shimon Monzon (Pentateuch, 1959; complete Bible, 1965 and later printings).<ref>{{cite book|title= Bibliography of the Hebrew Book|url= http://aleph.nli.org.il/F/PILYY8PJ3H682A78GYM7PAH7BYS3SAJBTJQVNTAT4Q9FPYBY38-04562?func=find-acc&acc_sequence=000090361/}}</ref> Unable to compete with larger, more modernized concerns, the Monsohn/Monzon Press closed in 1992. A grandson of the founders helped establish [[Keter Publishing House|Keter Press]], printer of the first edition of the ''[[Encyclopedia Judaica]]'' and still one of [[Israel]]'s leading printing establishments. Shimon Barmacz's son, Mordechai (b. 1948), established the Hebron Press in [[Kiryat Arba]]. Elyakim Monzon (b. 1927), son of Abraham-Leib's son Yosef (b. 1903), also engaged in printing. Moshe Monzon (b. 1958), grandson of Abraham-Leib's son Moshe, produces artistic tapestries. The prints produced by the A.L. Monsohn Lithography are today sought by collectors the world over.
