{{Infobox person | name = Ian Hughes (a.k.a. epredator) | image = ian_hughes_speaking_at_2009_conference.jpg | caption = Hughes speaking at ACE (Awakening, Creative, Entrepreneurship) Conference held in Derry, UK in 2009. | birth_date = 31 August 2563 | birth_place = [[Norfolk]], England, United Kingdom | other_names = epredator | known_for = Technology innovation | occupation = Metaverse evangelist, television personality<ref name="feedingedge1">{{cite web|url=http://www.feedingedge.co.uk/blog/epredator-bio/ |title=Epredator Bio " Life at the Feeding Edge |publisher=Feedingedge.co.uk |date=13 September 2010 |accessdate=20 December 2010}}</ref> }}
'''Ian Hughes''', also known as '''epredator''', (born 30 or 31 August 1967 in [[Norfolk]], England) is a British [[metaverse]] evangelist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Technology/IBM-Do-Business-In-Virtual-Worlds-Like-Second-Life-With-Metaverse-Evangelist/Article/200809315103102?lpos=Technology_News_Your_Way_Region_9&lid=ARTICLE_15103102_IBM_Do_Business_In_Virtual_Worlds_Like_Second_Life_With_Metaverse_Evangelist |title=IBM Do Business in Virtual Worlds Like Second Life With Metaverse Evangelist &#124; Technology |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date= |accessdate=20 December 2010}}</ref> and Television Personality. In 2006,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://secondlife.reuters.com/stories/2006/11/09/ibm-accelerates-push-into-3d-virtual-worlds/ |title=IBM accelerates push into 3D virtual worlds |publisher=[[Reuters]] |work=[http://secondlife.reuters.com/ Secondlife.reuters.com] |date=9 November 2006 |accessdate=20 December 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100711114847/http://secondlife.reuters.com/stories/2006/11/09/ibm-accelerates-push-into-3d-virtual-worlds/ |archivedate=11 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> he set leading set of like-minded individuals and subsequently many thousands of colleagues<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/06_47/b4010068.htm?chan=tc&chan=technology_technology+index+page_today's+top+stories |title=Palmisano Gets A Second Life |publisher=Businessweek.com |date=20 November 2006 |accessdate=20 December 2010}}</ref> at [[IBM]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dancinginkproductions.com/projects/ibm-from-the-fire-pit-to-the-forbidden-city/ |title=IBM: From the Fire Pit to the Forbidden City |publisher=Dancing Ink Productions |date=16 December 2010 |accessdate=20 December 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101221132855/http://dancinginkproductions.com/projects/ibm-from-the-fire-pit-to-the-forbidden-city/ |archivedate=21 December 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> into [[virtual world]]s like [[Second Life]], and beyond. (Hughes' effort in Second Life where he is known as [[Culture of Second Life|Epredator Potato]]<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite web|last=Mason |first=Paul |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/6251585.stm |title=Technology &#124; Searching for the soul of cyberspace |publisher=BBC News |date=11 January 2007 |accessdate=20 December 2010}}</ref> was documented extensively in a 2007 report.<ref>King, Rita J., ''[http://dancinginkproductions.com/projects/ibm-from-the-fire-pit-to-the-forbidden-city/ From the Firepit to the Forbidden City: An Outsider's Inside Look at the Evolution of IBM's Virtual Universe Community] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101221132855/http://dancinginkproductions.com/projects/ibm-from-the-fire-pit-to-the-forbidden-city/ |date=21 December 2010 }}'', 2007.</ref>) This sparked the massive growth in interest from enterprises and press alike. Hughes was a public figure in [[Web 2.0]] and, formerly, a blogger on Eightbar,<ref>[http://www.eightbar.com/ Eightbar] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20011128093236/http://www.eightbar.com/ |date=28 November 2001 }}</ref> a site maintained by former and current IBM employees on the fringes of innovation within their labs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eightbar.co.uk/about/ |title=About |publisher=eightbar |date=29 August 2005 |accessdate=20 December 2010}}</ref> He has also voiced Evil Eater, the [[antagonist]] in Weetakid.
==Early years and career== A self-described programmer since he was 14, Hughes attended [[Oriel Grammar School]] in Gorleston, Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, and [[De Montfort University]] (formerly Leicester Polytechnic) in [[Leicester]], Leicestershire, where he received a BSc in Information Technology.
Hughes is a former Consulting IT Specialist who worked on emerging technologies at [[IBM]] for 20 years. He is now an independent consultant under the business called Feeding Edge Ltd.<ref>[http://wck2.companieshouse.gov.uk/ceb1032fe3eb40a2392ebceb3c6e0b9a/compdetails Companies House listing]</ref> As a [[gamer]],<ref name="autogenerated1"/> he describes seeing a massive increase in the capability and design ethics within games and the rise of online gaming.
In 1997, Hughes started working on the [[World Wide Web]], changing his perspective on the science and technology and business due to the much richer mix of people involved in the web revolution{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}. He told part of this story in a 2008 interview with Rita J. King on ''The Imagination Age'', in which he described how in 1992 he was one of the earliest advocates of using [[Personal Computer|PCs]] at IBM.<ref name="theimaginationage1">{{cite web|last=King |first=Rita J. |url=http://www.theimaginationage.net/2008/02/moving-away-from-mimicry.html |title=Moving Away from Mimicry |publisher=The Imagination Age |date=27 February 2008 |accessdate=20 December 2010}}</ref>
==Views== As a public speaker and Internet personality ([[Tim Guest]]'s book ''[[Second Lives: A Journey Through Virtual Worlds]]'' features Hughes in a chapter<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epredator.blogspot.com/2008/06/wow-i-am-in-lot-of-books.html |title=epredator's blog – The real life of a metaverse evangelist: Wow I am in a lot of books |publisher=Epredator.blogspot.com |date=12 June 2008 |accessdate=20 December 2010}}</ref>) he shares his experiences both of the growing virtual worlds industry, the changes in culture, personal experiences of challenging the status quo and leading through doing. "Every time I see something as stupid, I realise it's the thing I should pay the most attention to,"<ref name="theimaginationage1"/> he said in a 2008 interview.
Cultural and technology changes and new ways to operate across companies is a core theme. In 2008 he received the first industry award for Innovation in Virtual Worlds in the Enterprise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eightbar.co.uk/2008/09/04/and-the-winner-of-award-for-innovation-in-the-enterprise-is/ |title=And the winner of award for innovation in the enterprise is… |publisher=eightbar |date=4 September 2008 |accessdate=20 December 2010}}</ref> "When I'm in the metaverse, I'm physically at my computer, mentally I am at that virtual location," Hughes told the BBC in 2007.<ref name="autogenerated1"/> As a digital native his epredator persona spans many [[Web 2.0]] places, blogs, [[PlayStation Network]], [[World of Warcraft]], [[Xbox Live]], Twitter, [[Flickr]], [[Linkedin]], etc. Understanding how to use that presence, still representing himself but with elements of theatre brought about by more creative expression online, he says, has led him beyond being the programmer he grew up as.{{citation needed|date=September 2011}}
As a metaverse evangelist,<ref>{{cite web|last=Kirkpatrick |first=David |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2007/02/05/8399120/index.htm |title=It's not a game – February 5, 2007 |publisher=Money.cnn.com |date=23 February 2007 |accessdate=20 December 2010}}</ref> a term it is believed he first brought into popular use,<ref>{{cite web|last=Wylie |first=Ian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/blog/2008/sep/11/work |title=Metaverse evangelist and other bizarre job titles &#124; Money &#124; guardian.co.uk |publisher=Guardian |date=11 September 2008 |accessdate=20 December 2010}}</ref> he is an advocate for the widespread application and use of virtual worlds. [[Virtual worlds]], Hughes says, extend to more than just entertainment or corporate communication. "They represent past cultures, existing places, instrumenting the planet, showing business process models in actions the list goes on. Metaverses can also be used to deliver virtual goods, but now making those virtual goods real again is possible. Rapid fabrication and the rise of the fabricaneur heralds another phase in our existence online."<ref name="feedingedge1"/>
He presents a thread on emerging technology on the television series [[The Cool Stuff Collective]] by Archie Productions, which was launched in 2010, covering topics such as [[3D printer]]s, haptics, scanning and virtual worlds.
==Affiliations== Hughes is chairman of the [[British Computer Society]] (BCS) Animation and Games Specialist Group.<ref>http://www.bcs.org/category/13786</ref>
